{"title_page": "Electoral history of Charles Tupper", "text_new": "{{Use Canadian English|date=April 2020}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{About||the biography of Charles Tupper|Charles Tupper}}\n\n[[File:Sir charles tupper.jpg|thumb|right|Tupper in 1896.]]\n\nThis article is the '''Electoral history of [[Charles Tupper|Sir Charles Tupper]]''', the sixth [[Prime Minister of Canada]].  A [[Conservatism in Canada|Conservative]], he became prime minister upon the resignation of Prime Minister [[Mackenzie Bowell|Sir Mackenzie Bowell]] over the [[Manitoba Schools Question]] in 1896.  Tupper was the shortest-serving prime minister, with a term of only 68 days.  He led his party in two general elections (1896, 1900) and lost both, to [[wilfrid Laurier|Sir Wilfrid Laurier]]\n\nPrior to [[Canadian Confederation|Confederation]] in 1867, Tupper was active in Nova Scotia politics, and was [[Premier of Nova Scotia]] from 1864 to 1867, when he was elected to the first [[House of Commons of Canada]].\n\n==Summary==\n[[File:Canada provinces 1889-1895.png|thumb|right|Canada had seven provinces, one territory and one semi-autonomous district during Tupper's term as Prime Minister.]]\n\nTupper had the [[List of Prime Ministers of Canada by time in office|shortest term in office of all twenty-three prime ministers]], serving for just 68 days in the spring of 1896.<ref>[https://lop.parl.ca/sites/ParlInfo/default/en_CA/People/primeMinisters PARLINFO:  Prime Ministers of Canada.]</ref>\n\nTupper was the second of three prime ministers from Nova Scotia, the others being [[John Sparrow David Thompson|Sir John Sparrow David Thompson]] and [[Robert L. Borden|Sir Robert Laird Borden]].\n\nHe became prime minister upon the resignation of [[Mackenzie Bowell|Sir Mackenzie Bowell]], who resigned after a Cabinet revolt over his handling of the [[Manitoba Schools Question]].  Tupper never sat in the Commons as prime minister, being sworn in as prime minister after the Commons was dissolved and the 1896 election called. He was defeated in the [[1896 Canadian federal election|1896 election]] by [[Wilfrid Laurier]].  Tupper maintained the leadership of the Conservative Party and ran again in the [[1900 Canadian federal election|general election of 1900]].  He was again defeated, including losing his own seat of [[Cape Breton (electoral district)|Cape Breton]].  He then retired, the last of the [[Fathers of Confederation]] to leave politics.\n\nTupper stood for election to the [[House of Commons of Canada]] twelve times, nine times  for the constituency of [[Cumberland (electoral district)|Cumberland]], Nova Scotia (1867, 1870, 1872, 1874, 1878 (twice), 1882, and 1887 (twice)), and three times for the constituency of [[Cape Breton (electoral district)|Cape Breton]] (1896 (twice), 1900). He was elected eleven times, including four times by acclamation (two [[ministerial by-elections]] (1870, 1878), one general election (1882), and one case where a sitting Member of Parliament resigned his seat to allow Tupper to re-enter the Commons (1896)). He lost at the constituency level only once, in his final election of 1900.  He served a total of 22 years, 7 months, 17 days in the Commons.<ref name = Tupper>[https://lop.parl.ca/sites/ParlInfo/default/en_CA/People/Profile?personId=6179 PARLINFO:   TUPPER, The Right Hon. Sir Charles, P.C.]</ref>\n\nPrior to his election to the House of Commons in 1867, Tupper was a member of the [[General Assembly of Nova Scotia]] and served as [[Premier of Nova Scotia]] from 1864 to 1867.<ref>[http://nslegislature.ca/index.php/about/past-premiers/ Nova Scotia Legislature:  Past Premiers.]</ref>\n\n==Federal general elections, 1896 and 1900==\n\nTupper led the combined Liberal-Conservative Party and Conservative Party in two general elections, losing both (1896, 1900).\n\n===Federal election, 1896===\n{{About||more detailed tables of election results|Canadian federal election, 1896}}\n{{About||information about the 8th Parliament, 1896 to 1900|8th Canadian Parliament}}\n{{About||information about Tupper and political events during the 8th Parliament|Charles Tupper#Leader of the Opposition.2C 1896.E2.80.931900}}\n\nThe 1896 election was the first election since Confederation in 1867 where [[John A. Macdonald|Sir John A. Macdonald]] did not lead the Conservatives.  Tupper became the formal leader of the Conservatives and was sworn in as Prime Minister shortly after the election was called.  Prior to the election, he had effectively led the government in the House of Commons on the [[Manitoba Schools Question]], since Prime Minister Bowell was in the Senate and had suffered a Cabinet revolt on his handling of the issue.  His main opponent in the general election was [[Wilfrid Laurier]], the leader of the [[Liberal Party of Canada|Liberals]].  Although Tupper and the Conservatives won the popular vote, Laurier and the Liberals won the majority of seats and formed the government, the first time at the federal level that the party with the greatest popular vote support did not form the government.\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" \n|+ Canadian Federal Election, 1896 - Parties, Leaders, Seats Won and Popular Vote\n|-\n!colspan=\"2\"|Party\n!Leaders!!Seats Won!!Popular Vote\n|-\n{{Canadian party colour|CA|Liberal|row-name}}\n|[[Wilfrid Laurier]]<sup>1</sup>||align=center|117||align=center|41.4%\n|-\n{{Canadian party colour|CA|PC|row}}\n|[[Conservative Party of Canada (1867\u20131942)|Conservative]]||rowspan=2|[[Charles Tupper]]<sup>2</sup>||align=center|71||align=center|44.4%\n|-\n{{Canadian party colour|CA|PC|row}}\n|[[Conservative Party of Canada (1867\u20131942)|Liberal-Conservative]]||align=center|15||align=center|3.8%\n|-\n{{Canadian party colour|CA|Independent|row}}\n|[[Independent Conservative]]||align=center|&ndash;||align=center|4||align=center|1.3%\n|-\n{{Canadian party colour|CA|Patrons of Industry|row-name}}\n|align=center|&ndash;||align=center|2||align=center|3.9%\n|-\n{{Canadian party colour|CA|Independent|row}}\n|[[McCarthyite candidates 1896|McCarthyite]]||[[Dalton McCarthy]]||align=center|2||align=center|1.3%\n|-\n{{Canadian party colour|CA|Independent|row}}\n|[[Independent politician#Canada|Independent]]||align=center|&ndash;||align=center|1||align=center|1.4%\n|-\n{{Canadian party colour|CA|Independent|row}}\n|[[Independent Liberal]]||align=center|&ndash;||align=center|1||align=center|0.2%\n|-\n{{Canadian party colour|CA|Liberal|row}}\n|[[Parti National (Quebec)|Nationalist]]||align=center|&ndash;||align=center|0||align=center|1.5%\n|-\n{{Canadian party colour|CA|Independent|row}}\n|[[Protestant Protective Association]]||align=center|&ndash;||align=center|0||align=center|0.6%\n{{Canadian party colour|CA|Independent|row}}\n|Unknown<sup>3</sup>||align=center|&ndash;||align=center|0||align=center|0.2%\n|-\n! colspan=3 align=left|Total\n! align=right| 213\n! align=right| 100.0%\n|-\n| align=\"center\" colspan=5|'''Source:'''  [https://web.archive.org/web/20090609211221/http://www2.parl.gc.ca/Sites/LOP/HFER/hfer.asp?Language=E Library of Parliament &ndash; History of Federal Ridings since 1867]\n|}\n\n<sup>1</sup> Leader of the Opposition when election was called;  Prime Minister after the election.<br />\n<sup>2</sup> Prime Minister shortly after election was called;  Leader of the Opposition after the election.<br />\n<sup>3</sup> Election returns in 1896 did not require candidates to declare party affiliation.  Some candidates did not list a party affiliation.\n\n===Federal election, 1900===\n\n{{About||more detailed tables of election results|Canadian federal election, 1900}}\n{{About||information about the 9th Parliament, 1901 to 1904|9th Canadian Parliament}}\n{{About||information about Tupper after the election|Charles Tupper#Later years.2C 1901.E2.80.931915}}\n\nAfter four years as Leader of the Opposition, Tupper led the Conservatives in the general election of 1900.  He was again defeated by the Liberals under Laurier, who increased both their popular vote and seats won.  Tupper lost his own seat in [[Cape Breton (electoral district)|Cape Breton]].  He retired from public life, the last of the [[Fathers of Confederation]] to leave Canadian politics.\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" \n|+ Canadian Federal Election, 1900 - Parties, Leaders, Seats Won and Popular Vote\n|-\n!colspan=\"2\"|Party\n!Leaders!!Seats Won!!Popular Vote\n|-\n{{Canadian party colour|CA|Liberal|row-name}}\n|[[Wilfrid Laurier]]<sup>1</sup>||align=center|128||align=center|50.3%\n|-\n{{Canadian party colour|CA|PC|row}}\n|[[Conservative Party of Canada (1867\u20131942)|Conservative]]||rowspan=2|[[Charles Tupper]]<sup>2</sup>||align=center|69||align=center|43.2%\n|-\n{{Canadian party colour|CA|PC|row}}\n|[[Conservative Party of Canada (1867\u20131942)|Liberal-Conservative]]||align=center|10||align=center|2.9%\n|-\n{{Canadian party colour|CA|Independent|row}}\n|[[Independent politician|Independent]]||align=center|&ndash;||align=center|3||align=center|1.4%\n|-\n{{Canadian party colour|CA|Independent|row}}\n|[[Independent Conservative]]||align=center|&ndash;||align=center|1||align=center|1.1%\n|-\n{{Canadian party colour|CA|Independent|row}}\n|[[Independent Liberal]]||align=center|&ndash;||align=center|1||align=center|0.5%\n|-\n{{Canadian party colour|CA|Independent|row}}\n|[[Independent Labour]]||align=center|&ndash;||align=center|1||align=center|0.4%\n|-\n{{Canadian party colour|CA|Labour|row-name}}\n|align=center|&ndash;||align=center|0||align=center|0.3%\n|-\n{{Canadian party colour|CA|Independent|row}}\n|Unknown<sup>3</sup>||align=center|&ndash;||align=center|0||align=center|0.0%<sup>4</sup>\n|-\n! colspan=3 align=left|Total\n! align=right| 213\n! align=right| 100.1%<sup>5</sup>\n|-\n| align=\"center\" colspan=5|'''Source:'''  [https://web.archive.org/web/20090609211221/http://www2.parl.gc.ca/Sites/LOP/HFER/hfer.asp?Language=E Library of Parliament &ndash; History of Federal Ridings since 1867]\n|}\n\n<sup>1</sup> Prime Minister when election was called;  Prime Minister after the election.<br />\n<sup>2</sup> Leader of the Opposition when election was called;  Leader of the Opposition after the election.<br />\n<sup>3</sup> Election returns in 1900 did not require candidates to declare party affiliation.  Some candidates did not list a party affiliation.<br />\n<sup>4</sup> \"Unknown\" candidates only received 27 votes nationally.<br />\n<sup>5</sup> Rounding error.\n\n== Federal constituency elections, 1867 to 1900 ==\n\nTupper stood for election to the Canadian House of Commons twelve times, nine times for the constituency of Cumberland, Nova Scotia (1867, 1870, 1872, 1874, 1878 (twice), 1882, and 1887 (twice)), and three times for the constituency of Cape Breton (1896 (twice), 1900). He won eleven of those elections and lost only once, in 1900.\n\n=== 1867 Federal election:  Cumberland ===\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" \n|+ [[1867 Canadian federal election|Federal Election, 1867]]: [[Cumberland (electoral district)|Cumberland]], Nova Scotia\n|-\n!colspan=\"2\"|Party\n!Candidate!!Popular Vote!! % \n|-\n{{Canadian party colour|CA|PC|row}}  \n|[[Conservative Party of Canada (1867\u20131942)|Conservative]]||[[File:Yes check.svg|15px|Yes]] [[Charles Tupper]]||align=center|1,368||align=center|51.8%\n|-\n{{Canadian party colour|CA|Anti-Confederation|row}}\n|[[Anti-Confederation Party|Anti-Confederation]]||[[William Annand]]||align=center|1,271||align=center|48.2%\n|-\n! colspan=3 align=center|Total!! align=right|2,639!! align=right| 100.0%\n|-\n| align=\"center\" colspan=5|'''Source:''' [https://lop.parl.ca/About/Parliament/FederalRidingsHistory/hfer.asp?Language=E&Search=Det&Include=Y&rid=164 Library of Parliament &ndash; History of Federal Ridings since 1867:  Cumberland]\n|- \n|}\n\n[[File:Yes check.svg|15px|Yes]] Elected.\n\n=== 1870 Federal Ministerial By-Election:  Cumberland ===\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" \n|+ [[Ministerial by-election|Federal Ministerial By-election]], June 15, 1870: [[Cumberland (electoral district)|Cumberland]], Nova Scotia<br />On Mr. Tupper being called to the [[Queen's Privy Council for Canada|Privy Council]] and appointed [[President of the Queen's Privy Council for Canada|President]] of that body, June 21, 1870\n|-\n!colspan=\"2\"|Party\n!Candidate!!Popular Vote!! % \n|-\n{{Canadian party colour|CA|PC|row}}\n|[[Conservative Party of Canada (1867\u20131942)|Conservative]]||[[File:Yes check.svg|15px|Yes]] '''X''' [[Charles Tupper]]||align=center|Acclaimed||align=center|&ndash;\n|-\n| align=\"center\" colspan=5|'''Source:''' [https://lop.parl.ca/About/Parliament/FederalRidingsHistory/hfer.asp?Language=E&Search=Det&Include=Y&rid=164 Library of Parliament &ndash; History of Federal Ridings since 1867:  Cumberland]\n|- \n|}\n\n[[File:Yes check.svg|15px|Yes]] Elected. <br />\n'''X''' Incumbent.\n\nAt this time, newly appointed Cabinet ministers had to stand for re-election, but it was customary for the other political party not to oppose the election.\n\n===1872 Federal election:  Cumberland===\n{| class=\"wikitable\" \n|+ [[1872 Canadian federal election|Federal Election, 1872]]: [[Cumberland (electoral district)|Cumberland]], Nova Scotia\n|-\n!colspan=\"2\"|Party\n!Candidate!!Popular Vote!! % \n|-\n{{Canadian party colour|CA|PC|row}}  \n|[[Conservative Party of Canada (1867\u20131942)|Conservative]]||[[File:Yes check.svg|15px|Yes]] '''X''' [[Charles Tupper]]||align=center|1,911||align=center|74.6%\n|-\n{{Canadian party colour|CA|Independent|row}} \n|Unknown||W. A. D. Morse||align=center|650||align=center|25.4%\n|-\n! colspan=3 align=center|Total!! align=right|2,561!! align=right| 100.0%\n|-\n| align=\"center\" colspan=5|'''Source:''' [https://lop.parl.ca/About/Parliament/FederalRidingsHistory/hfer.asp?Language=E&Search=Det&Include=Y&rid=164 Library of Parliament &ndash; History of Federal Ridings since 1867:  Cumberland]\n|- \n|}\n\n[[File:Yes check.svg|15px|Yes]] Elected. <br />\n'''X''' Incumbent.\n\n===1874 Federal election:  Cumberland===\n{| class=\