 Tupper]]||align=center|3,630||align=center|29.8%\n|-\n{{Canadian party colour|CA|PC|row}}  \n|[[Liberal-Conservative]]||[[File:Yes check.svg|15px|Yes]] '''X''' [[Hector Francis McDougall]]||align=center|3,430||align=center|28.1%\n|-\n{{Canadian party colour|CA|Liberal|row-name}} \n|[[Arthur Samuel Kendall]]||align=center|2,813||align=center|23.1%\n|-\n{{Canadian party colour|CA|Liberal|row-name}} \n|Joseph McPherson||align=center|2,328||align=center|19.1%\n|-\n! colspan=3 align=center|Total!! align=right|12,201!! align=right| 100.1%<sup>1</sup>\n|-\n| align=\"center\" colspan=5|'''Source:''' [https://lop.parl.ca/About/Parliament/FederalRidingsHistory/hfer.asp?Language=E&Search=Det&Include=Y&rid=107 Library of Parliament &ndash; History of Federal Ridings since 1867:  Cape Breton]\n|- \n|}\n\n<sup>1</sup> Rounding error <br />\n[[File:Yes check.svg|15px|Yes]] Elected.   Note:  the riding returned two members at this time. <br />\n'''X''' Incumbent\n\n===1900 Federal election:  Cape Breton===\n{| class=\"wikitable\" \n|+ [[1900 Canadian federal election|Federal Election, 1900]]: [[Cape Breton (electoral district)|Cape Breton]], Nova Scotia\n|-\n!colspan=\"2\"|Party\n!Candidate!!Popular Vote!! % \n|-\n{{Canadian party colour|CA|Liberal|row-name}} \n|[[File:Yes check.svg|15px|Yes]] [[Alexander Johnston (Canadian politician)|Alexander Johnston]]||align=center|3,922||align=center|26.0%\n|-\n{{Canadian party colour|CA|Liberal|row-name}} \n|[[File:Yes check.svg|15px|Yes]] [[Arthur Samuel Kendall]]||align=center|3,890||align=center|25.8%\n|-\n{{Canadian party colour|CA|PC|row}}  \n|[[Conservative Party of Canada (1867\u20131942)|Conservative]]|| '''X''' [[Charles Tupper]]||align=center|3,672||align=center|24.3%\n|-\n{{Canadian party colour|CA|PC|row}}  \n|[[Liberal-Conservative]]||'''X''' [[Hector Francis McDougall]]||align=center|3,604||align=center|23.9%\n|-\n! colspan=3 align=center|Total!! align=right|15,088!! align=right| 100.0%\n|-\n| align=\"center\" colspan=5|'''Source:''' [https://lop.parl.ca/About/Parliament/FederalRidingsHistory/hfer.asp?Language=E&Search=Det&Include=Y&rid=107 Library of Parliament &ndash; History of Federal Ridings since 1867:  Cape Breton]\n|- \n|}\n\n[[File:Yes check.svg|15px|Yes]] Elected.   Note:  the riding returned two members at this time. <br />\n'''X''' Incumbent\n\n==Nova Scotia elections, 1855 - 1863==\nTupper first stood for election to the [[Nova Scotia House of Assembly]] as a Conservative in the general election of 1855, winning in the County of Cumberland, defeating [[Joseph Howe]].  Although the [[Nova Scotia Liberal Party|Liberals]] won a majority of seats, gradual defections from the Liberal government to the Conservative opposition led to the Conservatives forming the government in 1857.  Tupper became Provincial Secretary, a Cabinet position.  In the 1859 election, Tupper was re-elected in Cumberland, but the Liberals again won a majority of seats and the Conservative government resigned.  In the general election of 1863, the Conservatives returned to power.  A year later, Premier Johnston retired and Tupper became Premier of Nova Scotia, a position he held until July 4, 1867.<ref>[http://www.biographi.ca/en/bio/tupper_charles_14E.html ''Dictionary of Canadian Biography'':  Tupper, Sir Charles.]</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n\n* [[Electoral history of Mackenzie Bowell]] - Tupper's predecessor as leader of the Conservative Party and as Prime Minister.\n* [[Electoral history of Wilfrid Laurier]] - Tupper's successor as Prime Minister.\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20090609211221/http://www2.parl.gc.ca/Sites/LOP/HFER/hfer.asp?Language=E History of Federal Ridings since 1867]\n\n[[Category:Electoral history of Canadian politicians|Tupper, Charles]]\n", "name_user": "Hiabc", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eSummary:typo", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Electoral_history_of_Charles_Tupper"}
{"title_page": "Marcos Maidana", "text_new": "{{short description|Argentine boxer}}\n{{Infobox boxer\n| name = Marcos Mymamasucksdick\n| image = Marcos Ren\u00e9 Maidana.jpg\n| caption = Maidana in 2009\n| realname = Marcos Ren\u00e9 Maidana\n| nickname = ''El Chino''\n| weight = {{plainlist|\n*[[Light welterweight]]\n*[[Welterweight]]\n}}\n| height = 5 ft 7 in\n| reach = 69 in\n| nationality = Argentine\n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|df=y|1983|7|17}}\n| birth_place = [[Margarita, Santa Fe|Margarita]], [[Santa Fe Province|Santa Fe]], Argentina\n| style = [[Orthodox stance|Orthodox]]\n| total = 40\n| wins = 35\n| KO = 31\n| losses = 5\n\n| draws = \n| no contests = \n}}\n\n'''Marcos Ren\u00e9 Maidana''' (born 17 July 1983) is an Argentine former [[professional boxer]] who competed from 2004 to 2014. He was a world champion in two [[weight class (boxing)|weight classes]], having held the [[WBA (Regular)]] [[super lightweight]] title from 2011 to 2012, and the WBA [[welterweight]] title from 2013 to 2014. A versatile [[pressure fighter|brawler]] in the ring, Maidana was well known for his formidable punching power, and was never [[technical knockout|stopped]] in any of his five losses. He famously outbrawled and withstood punishing blows from Floyd Mayweather, Jr. during their first bout, but lost to Mayweather via majority decision.\n\n==Professional career==\n===Light welterweight===\nMaidana started his career in 2004 before turning 21 years old. He fought his first 18 fights in his native Argentina over two years, winning all, including 17 via stoppage. On his 18th bout, he won the [[World Boxing Association|WBA]] Fedelatin [[Light welterweight|super lightweight]] title. Over the next year, Maidana only fought once in Argentina, five times in Germany and once in Panama. At the end of 2008, Maidana had a professional record of 25-0, with 24 stoppages.\n\n====Maidana vs. Kotelnik====\nOn 2 February 2009, Maidana challenged for his first world title, the WBA super lightweight championship against [[Andreas Kotelnik]] at the StadtHalle in [[Rostock]], Germany. Kotelnik beat Maidana via controversial [[split decision]], with the judges scoring the fight 115\u2013114, 113\u2013115, and 115\u2013113 in Kotelnik's favor.<ref>{{Citation|last=\u041c\u0438\u0440 \u0411\u043e\u043a\u0441\u0430 (The world of Boxing)|title=Marcos Maidana vs Andriy Kotelnik (07 02 2009)|date=2015-05-25|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=4hulDzkLrEM|accessdate=2018-02-14}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.boxingnews24.com/2009/02/kotelnik-defeats-maidana-in-a-war/|title=Kotelnik Defeats Maidana In a War \u00bb Boxing News|date=2009-02-08|work=Boxing News 24|access-date=2018-02-14|language=en-US}}</ref> Maidana was credited with landing 342 of 1241 punches thrown (28%), with 259 of them being power punches and Kotelnik was more accurate in landing 229 of his 655 thrown (35%).<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.boxingscene.com/compubox-punch-stats-khan-kotelnik-maidana-kotelnik--33744|title=CompuBox Punch Stats: Khan-Kotelnik, Maidana-Kotelnik|work=BoxingScene.com|access-date=2018-02-14|language=en-us}}</ref>\n\n====Maidana vs. Ortiz====\nMaidana's first fight in the [[United States]] was against [[Victor Ort\u00edz]], that took place on June 27, 2009 for the [[Interim championship|Interim]] [[World Boxing Association|WBA]] super lightweight title. Ortiz entered the fight with an eight-fight knockout streak.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://articles.latimes.com/2009/jun/27/sports/sp-boxing-ortiz27|title=Victor Ortiz fills void left by Oscar De La Hoya|last=Pugmire|first=Lance|date=2009-06-27|newspaper=Los Angeles Times|accessdate=2010-06-26}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.boxingnews24.com/2009/06/victor-ortiz-vs-marcos-rene-maidana-pre-fight-analysis|title=Victor Ortiz vs Marcos Maidana Pre-Fight Analysis|last=Blackwell|first=Brian Kenneth|date=2009-06-27|newspaper=Boxing News 24|accessdate=2010-06-26}}</ref> Both Ortiz and Maidana were knocked down in the first round. Ortiz knocked Maidana to the canvas twice in the second round. Ortiz suffered a cut in the fifth round and was knocked down in the sixth. The fight was stopped when the ringside physician would not let Ortiz continue to fight.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=jfgKr5wK9oY|title=Victor Ortiz Quits Like A Puto|date=2009-07-02|publisher=YouTube|accessdate=2014-05-16}}</ref> Many in the boxing media, including [[HBO]], chastised Ortiz for not wanting to continue in the fight.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://sports.espn.go.com/sports/boxing/columns/story?columnist=rafael_dan&id=4293871|title=Victor Ortiz falls apart against unrelenting Marcos Maidana|date=2009-06-29|publisher=ESPN|accessdate=2014-05-16}}</ref>\n\n====Maidana vs. Cayo====\nAfter his fight with Ortiz, it was rumoured that Maidana would face British boxer, and WBA super lightweight champion, [[Amir Khan (British boxer)|Amir Khan]], who won the title after defeating [[Andreas Kotelnik]].<ref>{{cite news |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/boxing/8469411.stm |title=Amir Khan set for US fight debut against Marcos Maidana |work=BBC Sport \u2013 Boxing |accessdate=14 April 2010 | date=2010-01-20}}</ref> However, Khan opted for [[Paulie Malignaggi]] as his next opponent. As a result, Maidana was scheduled to fight on 27 March 2010, against [[Victor Cayo]], whose record, at that time, was 24-0 with 75% of victories coming by way of knockout.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://boxrec.com/list_bouts.php?human_id=357688&cat=boxer |title=Professional boxing record of Victor Manuel Cayo |work=BoxRec |accessdate=14 April 2010}}</ref> Maidana knocked out the undefeated Cayo in the sixth round to retain his interim WBA super lightweight title and improve his record to 28-1, with 27 knockouts.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://sports.espn.go.com/sports/boxing/columns/story?columnist=rafael_dan&id=5035739 |title= ESPN \u2013 Marcos Maidana KOs Victor Cayo |work=ESPN Boxing |accessdate=14 April 2010}}</ref>\n\n====Maidana vs. Corley====\nAfter failing to secure a fight with [[Timothy Bradley]], Maidana fought and defeated [[DeMarcus Corley]] in August 2010.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.boxingscene.com/demarcus-corley-im-bringing-war-marcos-maidana--30188|title=DeMarcus Corley: I'm Bringing a War To Marcos Maidana!|work=BoxingScene.com|access-date=2018-02-14|language=en-us}}</ref> Despite knocking Corley down in the seventh round, Maidana had to go the distance for only the third time in his career, eventually securing the victory via [[unanimous decision]] 117\u2013110, 117\u2013110, and 115\u2013112. Even with the knockdown, many believed the fight was close. By round 11, Maidana was tired and both fighters traded in the final round.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.fightnews.com/Boxing/maidana-still-champion-58009 |title= Maidana still champion: Has trouble, but beats Corley |work=Fightnews.com |accessdate=29 August 2010}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.boxingscene.com/marcos-maidana-decisions-demarcus-corley-tough-fight--30459|title=Marcos Maidana Decisions DeMarcus Corley, Tough Fight|work=BoxingScene.com|access-date=2018-02-14|language=en-us}}</ref>\n\n====Maidana vs. Khan====\n{{Main|Amir Khan vs. Marcos Maidana}}\nBefore his fight with Corley, Maidana accused Khan and trainer [[Freddie Roach (boxing)|Freddie Roach]] of \"hypocrisy\" and called out Khan in an interview: \n{{cquote|I'll go to Khan's home soil to take the other portion of the WBA title, which belongs to me&nbsp;... They say they want me next when the cameras and mics are on. But when it comes to make the fight for real, Roach begs [[Golden Boy Promotions]] to keep Khan away from me.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.boxingscene.com/?m=show&id=30247 |title=Maidana: \"Khan, Roach hugging Talking and Fight Me!\" |work=BoxingScene.com |accessdate=29 August 2010}}</ref>}}\nKhan was looking for a good opponent to challenge him for his WBA title. One of his possible opponents was [[lightweight]] Champion [[Juan Manuel Marquez]]. Marquez decided not to move up in weight and stayed at lightweight. Maidana then stated his intention to fight Khan: \"Stop looking for possible opponents for next Khan 11 December in [[England]]. Stop looking for lightweight boxers and face the real [[Light welterweight|140-pounders]]. I'll go to Khan's home soil to take the other portion of the WBA title that belongs to me.\"<ref>{{cite journal|last=Vester|first=Mark|date=2010-08-29|title=Khan Answers Maidana: Wants To Fight on December 11|url=http://www.boxingscene.com/?m=show&id=30294|journal=BoxingScene|id=|accessdate=2010-10-24}}</ref> The fight was confirmed on 16 September to take place at the [[Mandalay Bay Events Center|Mandalay Bay]] in Las Vegas on 11 December. Khan was reported to earn at least $1.5 million compared to Maidana who had a purse of $550,000.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.espn.com/sports/boxing/news/story?id=5577437|title=Khan-Maidana bout finally slated for December|date=2010-09-15|website=ESPN.com|access-date=2017-10-17}}</ref>\n\nKhan successfully defended his title for the third time against Maidana. Khan knocked Maidana down with a combination of 2 body shots in the first round. Maidana was saved by the bell but somehow regained composure and continued to battle on. Khan dominated the scoring until tiring around round 7. Maidana rallied and midway through round 10 stunned Khan with a heavy right hand. Maidana landed a series of follow up uppercuts and rights but could not drop Khan. Khan then rallied to win rounds 11 and 12 to solidify a unanimous points decision. The scores were 114\u2013111, 114\u2013111, and 113\u2013112. Khan was open to a rematch. Khan landed 273 of 603 punches thrown (45%) and Maidana landed 156 of 767 thrown (20%).<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://en.espn.co.uk/boxing/sport/story/61962.html|title=Khan wins dramatic war with Maidana|work=ESPN.co.uk|access-date=2017-10-17|language=en-GB}}</ref> The fight was awarded Fight of the Year by the [[Boxing Writers Association of America]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/boxing/2016/05/05/amir-khan-vs-saul-canelo-alvarez-amir-khans-top-6-fights/|title=Amir Khan's Top 6 fights|last=Davies|first=Gareth A.|date=2016-05-05|work=The Telegraph|access-date=2017-10-17|language=en-GB|issn=0307-1235}}</ref>\n\n====Maidana vs. Morales====\n{{Main|\u00c9rik Morales vs. Marcos Maidana}}\nOn 10 February 2011, [[Golden Boy Promotions|Golden Boy]] promoter [[Richard Schaefer]] announced that a deal was reached for Maidana to next fight former three-weight world champion [[\u00c9rik Morales|\u00c9rik Moralez]] (51-6, 35 KOs) on 9 April at the [[MGM Grand Garden Arena|MGM Grand]] in [[Las Vegas]] on HBO [[Pay-per-view|PPV]] billed as 'Action Heroes'.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.espn.com/sports/boxing/news/story?id=6109137|title=Morales-Maidana headlines April HBO PPV card|date=2011-02-10|website=ESPN.com|access-date=2018-02-14}}</ref>\n\nIn the first round, Maidana came out with ferocity as expected and proceeded to batter his older opponent around the ring. He landed multiple power punches, including an uppercut that opened a huge swelling over Morales' left eye which worsened over the course of the fight, and when the Mexican walked back to his corner having taken a large amount of punishment in the opening three minutes most observers felt their predictions were being fulfilled. The one-sided nature of the bout continued for the next couple of rounds, but then at the end of the third round Morales begin to fight back and landed a hard combination to the head of Maidana and the tide began to turn. From the fourth round onwards and although he was effectively fighting with one eye, Morales gave as good as he got and was landing the cleaner more effective shots, albeit occasionally being swarmed by the sheer number of punches being landed in return by the relentless Maidana. The fight became a see-saw affair and then, in the eighth round, Morales hit Maidana with a huge left hook that almost stopped the Argentine. The next couple of rounds continued in this fashion, with Maidana using his strength and stamina to bully Morales and the Mexican using his sharper punching and ring intelligence to land effective counters and combinations. The fight was fast turning into a modern classic. In the championship rounds, Morales seemed to tire and Maidana took advantage, overwhelming him with his strength and punishing the ageing warrior continually to the head and body. Maidana finished the fight much the stronger of the two and his late surge gave him the win on the scorecards, 116\u2013112 twice with the third judge scoring the fight a draw, 114\u2013114. Most of the 7,154 fans in attendance booed the decision. [[ESPN]] scored the fight 114\u2013114.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.espn.com/sports/boxing/columns/story?columnist=rafael_dan&id=6319692|title=Maidana narrowly outpoints Morales|date=2011-04-10|website=ESPN.com|access-date=2018-02-14}}</ref>\n\n==== Maidana vs. Petrov ====\nMaidana was scheduled to defend his title 27 August 2011, against [[Robert Guerrero]], but Guerrero suffered a shoulder injury less than two weeks before the fight.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.boxingscene.com/guerrero-maidana-finalized-august-27-san-jose--40589|title=Guerrero-Maidana Finalized For August 27 in San Jose|work=BoxingScene.com|access-date=2018-02-14|language=en-us}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.boxingscene.com/schaefer-robert-guerrero-injured-maidana-fight-off--42775|title=Schaefer: Robert Guerrero Injured, Maidana Fight is Off|work=BoxingScene.com|access-date=2018-02-14|language=en-us}}</ref> On 8 September, Russian boxer [[Petr Petrov (boxer)|Petr Petrov]] (29-2-2, 13 KOs) was selected as Maidana's homecoming opponent for 23 September at Sociedad Alemana de Villa Ballester in [[Buenos Aires]], which would also mark the bout as his first defence of the WBA (Regular) title. Petrov came into the bout having never been stopped as a professional.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.boxingscene.com/maidana-vs-petrov-play-september-23rd-clash--43513|title=Maidana vs Petrov in Play For September 23rd Clash|work=BoxingScene.com|access-date=2018-02-14|language=en-us}}</ref> [[Breidis Prescott]], who was scheduled to fight [[Paul McCloskey]] in September in a title eliminator, stated he would have put himself forward to replace Guerrero, and knocked Maidana out.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.boxingscene.com/prescott-maidana-lucky-ve-knocked-his-ass-out--42805|title=Prescott: Maidana Lucky, Would've Knocked His Ass Out!|work=BoxingScene.com|access-date=2018-02-17|language=en-us}}</ref> Maidana became the first boxer to stop Petrov inside the distance and successfully retained his WBA title in round 4 of a one-sided fight. Petrov was in survival mode from the opening bell, trying to clinch. By round 3, Maidana began to see his punches land more and eventually dropped Petrov in round 4. Petrov got up and became a more defensive fighter for the remainder of the round until the final 30 seconds when Maidana landed a barrage of punches against the ropes, dropping Petrov again. The referee began the count, but almost immediately waived the count.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.boxingscene.com/marcos-maidana-blasts-petr-petrov-ko-win-four--44138|title=Marcos Maidana Blasts Petr Petrov, KO Win in Four|work=BoxingScene.com|access-date=2018-02-14|language=en-us}}</ref><ref>[http://www.badlefthook.com/2011/9/23/2445881/maidana-vs-petrov-results-tko-4-win-maidana-no-trouble-argentina Maidana vs Petrov Results: No Trouble for Maidana in Argentina, TKO-4 Win]. Bad Left Hook. Retrieved on 2014-05-04.</ref>\n\n===Welterweight===\n\n==== Maidana vs. Alexander ====\nIn December 2011 it was announced that Maidana would move up to [[welterweight]] to fight former [[World Boxing Council|WBC]] and [[International Boxing Federation|IBF]] light welterweight champion [[Devon Alexander]], who was also moving up in weight, on 25 February 2012, at the [[Scottrade Center]] in [[St. Louis, Missouri]] in a 10-round bout. Alexander was the betting favourite going into the bout.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.boxingscene.com/devon-alexander-eyes-impressive-display-with-maidana--47929|title=Devon Alexander Eyes Impressive Display With Maidana|work=BoxingScene.com|access-date=2018-02-14|language=en-us}}</ref> Maidana seemed uncomfortable in his first fight at the new weight as Alexander dominated the fight and went on to win a lopsided unanimous decision. The three judges scored the fight 100\u201390, 100\u201390, and 99\u201391 for Alexander. Alexander landed 168 punches compared to the 93 landed by Maidana. Speaking of the loss, Maidana said, \"I was slower. He was very fast and complicated.\"<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.espn.co.uk/boxing/story/_/id/7616792/devon-alexander-tops-marcos-maidana-10-round-decision|title=Alexander tops Maidana with 10-round decision|work=ESPN.com|access-date=2018-02-14}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.badlefthook.com/2012/2/26/2825116/maidana-vs-alexander-results-unanimous-decision-shutout-scores-hbo-boxing-news-recap|title=Maidana vs Alexander Results: Devon Alexander Shines in St. Louis, Gets Back on Track With Wide Win|work=Bad Left Hook|access-date=2018-02-14}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.boxingscene.com/alexander-hurts-punishes-dominates-maidana-win--49998|title=Alexander Hurts, Punishes and Dominates Maidana To Win|work=BoxingScene.com|access-date=2018-02-14|language=en-us}}</ref>\n\n==== Maidana vs. Soto Karass ====\nIn July 2012, [[Showtime (TV network)|Showtime]] announced that Maidana would fight [[Jesus Soto Karass]] (26-7-3, 17 KOs) on the [[Canelo \u00c1lvarez|Saul \u00c1lvarez]] vs. [[Josesito L\u00f3pez|Josesito Lopez]] undercard at the [[MGM Grand Las Vegas|MGM Grand]] in Las Vegas on 15 September.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.boxingscene.com/maidana-vs-soto-karass-play-canelo-lopez--55011|title=Maidana vs. Soto Karass in Play For Canelo-Lopez|work=BoxingScene.com|access-date=2018-02-14|language=en-us}}</ref> Maidana won the fight by eighth-round [[Knockout#Technical knockout|TKO]] in a back-and-forth slugfest. Both boxers started off fast while trading blows. Maidana looked to set up his attack behind a jab. Midway through the fight, Maidana began to tire and Karass took over. In round 7, Maidana finally had a point taken off for continuing to hit on the break. Maidana landed a right hand, dropping Karass. In round 8, Maidana continued to attack Karass against the ropes before referee Kenny Bayliss stopped the fight.<ref>[http://espn.go.com/boxing/story/_/id/8382678/marcos-maidana-wins-bitter-brawl-jesus-soto-karras Marcos Maidana wins bitter brawl over Jesus Soto Karras \u2013 ESPN]. Espn.go.com (2012-09-16). Retrieved on 2014-05-04.</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.boxingscene.com/marcos-maidana-powers-past-jesus-soto-karass-eight--57147|title=Marcos Maidana Powers Past Jesus Soto Karass in Eight|work=BoxingScene.com|access-date=2018-02-14|language=en-us}}</ref> According to [[CompuBox]] Stats, Maidana landed 213 of 539 punches thrown (40%) and Karass landed 179 of his 748 thrown.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.boxingscene.com/forums/view.php?pg=maidana-soto-karass-compubox|title=Maidana vs. Soto-Karass - CompuBox Stats|website=www.boxingscene.com|language=en|access-date=2018-02-14}}</ref>\n\nOn 29 November, it was announced that, whilst waiting for a big fight, Maidana would fight the largely unknown Mexican boxer [[Martin \u00c1ngel Mart\u00ednez]] (13-3-1, 9 KOs) on 12 December at the Luna Park Stadium in Buenos Aires, for the vacant WBA Inter-Continental welterweight title.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.boxingscene.com/marcos-maidana-face-angel-martinez-on-dec-12th--59854|title=Marcos Maidana To Face Angel Martinez on Dec. 12th|work=BoxingScene.com|access-date=2018-02-17|language=en-us}}</ref> In front of over 7,000 local fans, Maidana won the fight by KO in the third round. Maidana started off slow, but picked up the pace in round 2 before landing a powerful left hook to body, dropping Mart\u00ednez for the full 10 count. Maidana stated his intention to fight [[Paulie Malignaggi]] or [[Robert Guerrero]] next.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.boxingscene.com/marcos-maidana-knocks-angel-martinez-out-three--60404|title=Marcos Maidana Knocks Angel Martinez Out in Three|work=BoxingScene.com|access-date=2018-02-17|language=en-us}}</ref>\n\n====Maidana vs. Lopez====\nMaidana scored a TKO over welterweight contender [[Josesito Lopez]] in the sixth round of a 9 June 2013 fight. Maidana had injured his hip in the second round and Lopez capitalized, tagging his opponent with hard shots. Maidana was able to reverse the tide and hurt Lopez with an overhand right in the sixth round that dropped him to the canvas.<ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/sports/boxing/2013/06/09/marcos-maidana-stops-josesito-lopez-in-6th-round/2404791/ | work=USA Today | first=Mike | last=Coppinger | title=Marcos Maidana stops Josesito Lopez in 6th round | date=2013-06-09}}</ref> Lopez later said that Maidana is the hardest puncher he ever faced.<ref>[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=6rvpSYFVnzg Josesito Lopez: Biggest Puncher I have ever Faced], [[Elie Seckbach|EsNews]] (October 22, 2015)</ref>\n\n====Maidana vs. Broner====\n{{Main|Adrien Broner vs. Marcos Maidana}}\nIn October 2013, it was announced that [[Adrien Broner]] would make his first defense of the WBA welterweight title against Maidana. Originally scheduled as a PPV fight, Golden Boy Promotions and Showtime Sports announced it would take place on regular Showtime on 14 December.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.espn.com/boxing/story/_/id/9885991/adrien-broner-marcos-maidana-taken-ppv-moved-san-antonio-part-late-year-schedule-changes|title=Broner-Maidana off PPV, moved to San Antonio|work=ESPN.com|access-date=2017-10-04}}</ref> The fight was due to take place at the MGM Grand arena, but later move to the [[Alamodome]] in [[San Antonio]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.badlefthook.com/2013/10/26/5033024/broner-vs-maidana-moved-off-ppv-alexander-porter-card-scrapped-and|title=Broner-Maidana off PPV, SHO consolidates cards|work=Bad Left Hook|access-date=2017-10-04}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.badlefthook.com/2013/10/31/5052370/broner-vs-maidana-fighters-make-statements-at-first-press-conference|title=Broner, Maidana start talking at first presser|work=Bad Left Hook|access-date=2017-10-04}}</ref> Broner had stated before the fight that he did not take training camp seriously for the Malignaggi fight, and that he was going to make a statement in his first defense. There was a crowd of 11,312 at the Alamodome, with Broner a 5 to 1 betting favorite. From the opening bell, Maidana swarmed Broner, punishing him to the body and the head. In the second round, a left hook sent Broner down for the first time in his career. Broner recovered and seemed to be on the verge of taking control over a tiring Maidana, but a right to the body followed by a left hook to the head once again put Broner down in round 8. Following the knockdown, Maidana had a point deducted for a headbutt. Maidana punished Broner for the remainder of the fight, winning the fight via unanimous decision and giving Broner his first loss as a professional.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.badlefthook.com/2013/12/14/5212036/broner-vs-maidana-results-marcos-maidana-solves-the-problem-beats|title=Marcos Maidana solves 'The Problem,' beats Adrien Broner in San Antonio|last=|first=|date=December 14, 2013|website=|publisher=|access-date=December 27, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://bleacherreport.com/articles/1889412-broner-vs-maidana-results-winner-scorecard-and-analysis|title=Adrien Broner vs. Marcos Maidana Results: Winner, Scorecard and Analysis|last=|first=|date=|website=|publisher=|access-date=December 27, 2016}}</ref> The judges scored the fight 115\u2013110, 116\u2013109, and 117\u2013109 in favour of Maidana. Maidana had now won four consecutive fights under the tutelage of boxing trainer [[Robert Garcia (American boxer)|Robert Garcia]]. Broner immediately left the ring following the announcement. Fans booed and threw drinks at Broner as he made his way back to his dressing room.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.espn.com/boxing/story/_/id/10140099/marcos-maidana-unanimously-outpoints-adrien-broner-wba-welterweight-title|title=Maidana takes Broner's WBA welterweight title|work=ESPN.com|access-date=2017-10-04}}</ref>\n\nBroner later apologized, saying, \"I'm sorry for running out on all the fans after my fight. That was wrong of me as a fighter.\" Maidana said he was open to a rematch if it made sense. Broner later said, \"I'll tell you one thing: Make a rematch. I don't need a warm-up fight. I want a rematch.\" Maidana landed 269 of 964 total punches (28%) and 231 of 663 power shots (35%). Broner connected on 149 of 400 total punches (37%) and 122 of 292 power shots (42%).<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/boxing/25388305|title=Marcos Maidana defeats Adrien Broner to win welterweight title|date=2013-12-15|work=BBC Sport|access-date=2017-10-04|language=en-GB}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.espn.co.uk/boxing/story/_/id/10138978/marcos-maidana-unloads-pulls-huge-upset-adrien-broner|title=Maidana unloads, upsets Broner|work=ESPN.com|access-date=2017-10-04}}</ref> Showtime Executive Vice President [[Stephen Espinoza]] announced the fight drew 1.3 million viewers, putting it as the third-highest rated fight for the network since it began keeping track of individual fights in 2009.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.boxingscene.com/broner-maidana-draws-13-million-viewers-on-showtime--72850|title=Broner-Maidana Draws 1.3 Million Viewers on Showtime - Boxing News|website=www.boxingscene.com|language=en-us|access-date=2017-10-04}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.badlefthook.com/2014/1/10/5296648/adrien-broner-vs-marcos-maidana-ii-broner-picks-option-rematch-showtime-golden-boxing-news+&cd=6&hl=en&ct=clnk&gl=uk|title=Maidana-Broner II: April 19 or April 26|work=Bad Left Hook|access-date=2017-10-04}}</ref>\n\nBroner exercised his contractual rematch clause on 15 January 2014 to fight Maidana in a rematch. He told ESPN, \"My mind is set on war. I had a bad night. He was the better man that night, but he didn't beat me. He outhustled me. I respect everything. I respect him. But I'm ready to go back to war and get my belt back.\" After Maidana beat Broner, he became a candidate to fight [[Floyd Mayweather Jr.]] on 3 May on Showtime PPV. The other close candidate was Amir Khan. Maidana's manager Sebastian Contursi believed his fighter deserved a big money fight.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.espn.co.uk/boxing/story/_/id/10275821/adrien-broner-exercises-rematch-clause-fight-marcos-maidana-welterweight-title|title=Broner exercises rematch clause with Maidana|work=ESPN.com|access-date=2017-10-04}}</ref> ESPN reported the rematch could take place in April 2014 in [[California]] at the [[Dignity Health Sports Park|StubHub Center]] or again at the Alamodome.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.badlefthook.com/2014/1/10/5296648/adrien-broner-vs-marcos-maidana-ii-broner-picks-option-rematch-showtime-golden-boxing-news+&cd=6&hl=en&ct=clnk&gl=uk|title=Maidana-Broner II: April 19 or April 26|work=Bad Left Hook|access-date=2017-10-04}}</ref>\n\n====Maidana vs. Mayweather Jr.====\n{{Main|Floyd Mayweather Jr. vs. Marcos Maidana}}\nIn February 2014, despite interest in a bout with [[Amir Khan (boxer)|Amir Khan]], [[Floyd Mayweather Jr.]] announced that he would fight Maidana on 3 May 2014, in a [[Undisputed champion#Unified champion|unification]] bout at [[MGM Grand Garden Arena]], with Mayweather's [[World Boxing Council|WBC]] and ''[[The Ring (magazine)|The Ring]]'' welterweight titles at stake, as well as Maidana's WBA (Super) welterweight title.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://ringtv.craveonline.com/news/320735-push-live-when-announcement-is-made-floyd-mayweather-jr-picks-marcos-maidana-over-amir-khan|title=Floyd Mayweather Jr. picks Marcos Maidana over Amir Khan|work=Ring TV|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140301210438/http://ringtv.craveonline.com/news/320735-push-live-when-announcement-is-made-floyd-mayweather-jr-picks-marcos-maidana-over-amir-khan|archivedate=March 1, 2014|url-status=dead|accessdate=February 24, 2014|df=mdy-all}}</ref> Maidana won the WBA title in December 2013 against Mayweather prot\u00e9g\u00e9, Adrien Broner. Mayweather tweeted the news the day after his 37th birthday. The [[Barclays Center]] in [[Brooklyn]] also made a case to showcase the fight. Mayweather explained why he chose Maidana, \"Marcos Maidana's last performance immediately brought him to my attention. He is an extremely skilled fighter who brings knockout danger to the ring. I think this is a great fight for me and he deserves the opportunity to see if he can do what 45 others have tried to do before him \u2013 beat me.\" Maidana was a 12-to-1 underdog going into the fight.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.espn.co.uk/boxing/story/_/id/10513894/floyd-mayweather-jr-lines-marcos-maidana-next-fight|title=Mayweather lines up Maidana for next fight|work=ESPN.com|access-date=2017-08-29}}</ref>\n\nIn front of a sold-out crowd of 16,268, in what was one of his toughest fights, Mayweather won the bout via [[majority decision]], with scores of 114\u2013114, 117\u2013111, and 116\u2013112. Maidana came out aggressive and maintained that stance throughout the fight forcing Mayweather to engage. CompuBox revealed that Mayweather was hit more times than any of his previous 38 bouts that have been covered by them. Mayweather landed 230 of his 426 punches thrown (54%) while Maidana landed 221 of 858 (26%). Many times in the fight Maidana threw shots at different angles, forcing Mayweather against the ropes. According to Mayweather in the post fight interview, Maidana's aggressive approach made him change his style of fighting.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.dailymail.co.uk/sport/boxing/article-2619682/Floyd-Mayweather-vs-Marcos-Maidana-Amir-Khan-vs-Luis-Collazo-LIVE.html|title=Floyd Mayweather retains title despite valiant effort from Marcos Maidana, while and Amir Khan gives masterclass in Luis Collazo win|date=May 3, 2014|work=Daily Mail|accessdate=May 3, 2014|location=London}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/sports/boxing/2014/05/04/floyd-mayweather-maidana-majority-decision-las-vegas/8667891/|title=Floyd Mayweather beats Marcos Maidana, but crowd unhappy|work=USA TODAY|access-date=2017-08-29|language=en}}</ref>\n\nMaidana was guaranteed a purse of $1.5 million, which would also include TV revenue from his native Argentina and PPV share. Mayweather earned a minimum $32 million. There were calls for an immediate rematch. Mayweather said, \"He put pressure on me and that's when I decided to fight differently,\" Mayweather said. \"I stood there and fought him. He's a good fighter, I take nothing away from him [...] This was a tough, competitive fight. This is what fans want to see. \"I want to give fans an exciting fight. Normally, I box and move. Tonight, I gave fans an exciting fight.\" Maidana felt he won the fight, believing he gave Mayweather his toughest fight ever. Speaking through a translator, he said, \"I definitely think I won. Floyd had never been hit by a man before. I had to change the gloves [after a last-minute problem with his original gloves on Friday] and I still gave him a great fight.\"<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.espn.co.uk/boxing/story/_/id/10879956/floyd-mayweather-jr-scores-majority-decision-marcos-maidana-welterweight-unification-fight|title=Mayweather decisions Maidana in thriller|work=ESPN.com|access-date=2017-08-29}}</ref>\n\nThe generated around 900,000 although exact figures were not released by Showtime. The revenue of PPV sale amounted to $58 million.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.si.com/boxing/counter-punch/2014/05/29/floyd-mayweather-marcos-maidana-boxing|title=Mayweather-Maidana fight generates less than 1 million pay per view buys|work=SI.com|access-date=2017-08-29}}</ref>\n\n====Maidana vs. Mayweather Jr. II====\n{{main|Floyd Mayweather Jr. vs. Marcos Maidana II}}\nOn 10 July 2014, Mayweather made the announcement that a rematch with Maidana (35\u20134, 31 KOs) was confirmed. The fight was to take place on 13 September 2014, at the MGM Grand Garden Arena, with Mayweather's WBA (Super), WBC and ''The Ring'' welterweight titles at stake, as well as Mayweather's WBC [[light middleweight]] title. The fight was billed as \"Mayhem\".<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/kurtbadenhausen/2014/07/10/floyd-mayweather-announces-rematch-versus-marcos-maidana/+&cd=7&hl=en&c|title=Floyd Mayweather Announces Rematch Versus Marcos Maidana|last=Badenhausen|first=Kurt|work=Forbes|access-date=2017-08-29|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www1.skysports.com/boxing/news/12040/9378594/floyd-mayweather-confirms-marcos-maidana-rematch-on-september-13|title=Floyd Mayweather confirms Marcos Maidana rematch on September 13|work=Sky Sports|accessdate=July 14, 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.worldboxingnews.net/news/2014/07/30/mayweather-and-maidana-to-fight-for-two-weight-wbc-titles.html|title=Mayweather and Maidana to fight for two-weight WBC titles|work=World Boxing News|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140802034800/http://www.worldboxingnews.net/news/2014/07/30/mayweather-and-maidana-to-fight-for-two-weight-wbc-titles.html|archivedate=August 2, 2014|url-status=dead|accessdate=July 30, 2014}}</ref>\n\nIn front of 16,144 at the MGM Grand, Mayweather defeated Maidana via unanimous decision. Unlike the first fight, Mayweather came out better prepared for Maidana's style. The final judges' scores were 115\u2013112, 116\u2013111, and 116\u2013111. ESPN scored it wider for Mayweather at 119\u2013108. Despite a moment at the end of round 3 where Maidana rocked Floyd, Mayweather did not allow Maidana to land any overhand right, with the punch stats showing Maidana connecting 128 of 572 shots (22%). Mayweather had 51% connect rate landing 166 of 326.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://bleacherreport.com/articles/2197732-mayweather-vs-maidana-2-live-round-by-round-results-and-highlights|title=Mayweather vs. Maidana 2: Live Round-by-Round Results and Highlights|author=Chen, Brian|date=2014-09-13|publisher=[[Bleacher Report]]|accessdate=2016-12-27}}</ref>\n\nA bizarre moment occurred in round 8, whilst in a headlock, Maidana appeared to have bitten Mayweather's left hand. Mayweather explained this in the post fight, \"I didn't know what it was. Something happened and then my fingers were numb. After the eighth round my fingers were numb. I could only use my other hand. He bit me. I realized he bit me. We were tangled in the middle of the ring and all of a sudden I felt something on my left hand.\" Maidana denied the bite, \"Maybe he thinks I'm a dog, but I never bit him. He was rubbing my eyes that round. He may have had his glove in my mouth, but I never bit him.\" After round 9, Maidana appeared to be confused as he started walking towards the wrong corner. Mayweather immediately ran towards him to point to his corner, much to the amusement of the crowd. Maidana was unhappy with the final verdict and thought he won the fight, \"If the judges want to give the fight to fighters that run, they can give it to him. I was attacking all the time. Maybe I'm wrong, but I thought that I was the aggressor. I kept my plan to be aggressive but he kept holding and pushing. I don't want to waste my time with a third fight. I trained with all my heart to get this type of result. This is not fair. There's not reason for another fight.\" For the sequel, Mayweather earned a minimum of $32 million and Maidana earned a career high $3 million.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.espn.co.uk/boxing/story/_/id/11522417/floyd-mayweather-jr-scores-unanimous-decision-marcos-maidana-rematch|title=Mayweather decisions Maidana in rematch|work=ESPN.com|access-date=2017-08-29}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.badlefthook.com/2014/9/14/6146209/mayweather-vs-maidana-results-floyd-mayweather-wins-easier-decision|title=Mayweather wins easier in rematch with Maidana|work=Bad Left Hook|access-date=2017-08-29}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.sbnation.com/2014/9/14/6146479/mayweather-vs-maidana-2-results-floyd-mayweather-wins-rematch-by|title=Mayweather takes decision win over Maidana|last=Brookhouse|first=Brent|date=2014-09-14|website=SBNation.com|access-date=2017-08-29}}</ref>\n\nThe fight did well on PPV, a reported 925,000 households bought the fight, generating $60 million. The live gate grossed nearly $15 million, putting it at number 5 in the top 35 boxing gates.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.badlefthook.com/2014/9/19/6526031/mayweather-maidana-ii-does-good-numbers-on-ppv-and-live-gate+&|title=Mayweather-Maidana II performs well on PPV|work=Bad Left Hook|access-date=2017-08-29}}</ref>\n\n===Retirement===\nOn 9 August 2016, Maidana officially announced his retirement from professional boxing at the age of 33, allegedly moving into an advisory role.<ref>http://www.skysports.com/boxing/news/12183/10529985/marcos-maidana-announces-retirement-from-boxing</ref> Maidana wrote in a letter addressed to boxing friends on social media: \"After a long time out of the ring and after giving it a lot of thought since my last fight I've decided to hang up the gloves for good. Probably my decision would not surprise much as I had given hints of it in the last few months. But at this time I am making it official.\" Maidana finished with a career record of 35 wins in 40 fights, 31 wins coming by way of knockout and 5 decision losses.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.espn.co.uk/boxing/story/_/id/17258239/marcos-maidana-retires-age-33|title=Maidana retires at 33|access-date=2016-08-10}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nMaidana said that he is of [[Indigenous peoples of the Americas|indigenous]] descent.<ref>In a YouTube video titled, \"''maidana gets new tattoo EsNews Boxing''\", an interviewer asked Maidana, \"''Do they have Indians in uh, Argentina? I'm sure they do. You have Indians in Argentina, Marco?''\" The translator translated Maidana's response to this question as, \"''Yeah, absolutely. There's a little bit of everything. Argentina's huge! And he, he comes from uh, Indian descent... like tribes from, from Argentina''\". The interviewer's quote starts at the [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=IFL1ZbraJaI&t=4m18s 4:18 mark of the video], and the interviewer's quote ends at the 4:23 mark of the video. The translator's quote starts at the [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=IFL1ZbraJaI&t=4m26s 4:26 mark of the video], and the translator's quote ends at 4:38 mark of the video.</ref> He said that he liked the \"Chino\" nickname, and said that he was not going to change it.<ref>In a YouTube video titled, \"''Marcos Maidana - Post-Fight Interview - SHOWTIME Boxing''\" which was published to YouTube on December 14, 2013, a reporter asked Maidana if he was going to change his nickname to something else. [[Robert Garcia (American boxer)|Robert Garcia]] translated Maidana's response to this question as, \"''I'm always going to be Chino. I like my name.''\" The reporter's question starts at the [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=RJBsML9jI5s&t=0m0s start of the video], and the reporter's quote ends at the 0:03 mark of the video. Robert Garcia's quote starts at the [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=RJBsML9jI5s&t=0m9s 0:09 mark of the video], and Garcia's quote ends at the 0:12 mark of the video.</ref> Maidana said that he would support his son if he wanted to become a boxer, though he does not want him to be one.<ref>In a YouTube video titled, \"''Marcos Maidana Rolling In A Limo Exclusive video - esnews boxing''\", which was published to YouTube on September 12, 2012, an interviewer asked Maidana what he would tell his son if his son told him that he wanted to become a boxer. The translator translated Maidana's response as, \"''Boxing's a hard sport, very uh dangerous sport, you know. If that's what my son wants to do, and that's his destiny, uh, you know, God bless him, you know, but uh. He doesn't, he wouldn't want his son to fight, but uh if that's uh, something that he chooses to, to do, he's gonna support him.''\" This quote starts at the [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=zSaF_h34WBk&t=8m40s 8:40 mark of the video], and the quote ends at the 8:56 mark of the video.</ref>\n\n==Professional boxing record==\n{{BoxingRecordSummary\n|ko-wins=31\n|dec-wins=4\n|dec-losses=5\n}}\n{|class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:center; font-size:95%\"\n|-\n!{{abbr|No.|Number}}\n!Result\n!Record\n!Opponent\n!Type\n!Round, time\n!Date\n!Location\n!Notes\n|-\n|40\n|{{no2}}Loss\n|35\u20135\n|style=\"text-align:left;\"|{{flagicon|USA}} [[Floyd Mayweather Jr.]]\n|UD\n|12\n|[[Floyd Mayweather Jr. vs. Marcos Maidana II|13 Sep 2014]]\n|style=\"text-align:left;\"|{{flagicon|USA}} {{small|MGM Grand Garden Arena, Paradise, Nevada, U.S.}}\n|style=\"text-align:left;\"|{{small|For [[WBA (Super)]], WBC, ''The Ring'', and lineal welterweight titles;<br>For [[list of WBC world champions#Super welterweight|WBC]] and lineal light middleweight titles}}\n|-\n|39\n|{{no2}}Loss\n|35\u20134\n|style=\"text-align:left;\"|{{flagicon|USA}} [[Floyd Mayweather Jr.]]\n|MD\n|12\n|[[Floyd Mayweather Jr. vs. Marcos Maidana|3 May 2014]]\n|style=\"text-align:left;\"|{{flagicon|USA}} {{small|MGM Grand Garden Arena, Paradise, Nevada, U.S.}}\n|style=\"text-align:left;\"|{{small|Lost WBA welterweight title;<br>For [[list of WBC world champions#Welterweight|WBC]], ''[[list of The Ring world champions#Welterweight|The Ring]]'', and lineal welterweight titles}}\n|-\n|38\n|{{yes2}}Win\n|35\u20133\n|style=\"text-align:left;\"|{{flagicon|USA}} [[Adrien Broner]]\n|UD\n|12\n|[[Adrien Broner vs. Marcos Maidana|14 Dec 2013]]\n|style=\"text-ali